I. The Last Message

So if you read me now as targeting you,
If that is what your posting comes to mean,
If Hillary, that word, that fatal cue,
Makes violence of what moved there in between,

Then let this be the last thing that I send.
I am sorry. Strange, perhaps. But I
Assumed you knew the stakes before the end,
Though I gave you no cause to know them by.

It was so long ago. I gave no sign.
I answered by not answering at all.
Or so it looked. Beneath that blank design
Something impossible began to fall.

And if this reaches you in any way,
Let it stand once, and then be done today.

II. The Lifting Away

The whole set of beautiful moments was
Lifted away somehow. I leave the why
To endless rumination, to the cause
That does not show itself, though years go by.

But to have you set there before me so,
As if by powers beyond my comprehension,
Then and now, by agencies I know
Only as absence sharpened into tension—

Nothing could hurt so much. Nothing could break
The whole shape of a life the way this did:
The sudden fact that you were real could make
The past split open where the past was hid.

I met you. That remains. The rest withdrew.
And all my history rearranged through you.

III. Brooklyn / HAPPY

Especially Brooklyn. That Brooklyn where
I never saw you after, not one time,
Unless some buried memory still lies there
Uncounted somewhere underneath the grime.

And never seeing you again made strange
The borough and the world that held its place.
Reality itself began to change,
As if the air had opened round your face.

Yet even that distortion carried light:
It makes the world feel less a shuttered part,
More like a vaster realm where, through the night,
The lost may reappear and restart.

So I send this card. Its keyword is your way:
HAPPY—the word you give the coming day.


IV. HAPPY

I saw while making it that this was yours:
That word on blue-sky mornings, lightly said
As if tomorrow opened of itself in doors
Already gold before the day had spread.

Happy Caturday. Happy Thick Trunk Day.
Whatever form the blessing had to take,
You named the hour before it came that way,
As if the saying helped the morning wake.

So I include this odd Shakespearean card,
This little engine built of quote and sign,
Because one word of yours still lingers hard
Against the dark distortion worked in mine.

If this must be the last, then let it be
A day declared before the eye can see.
